& SCIENCE</font></center>
<p>
<B><font size=3> Highly Toxic: The Superfund Assault on Common Sense
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Raymond Keating</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Small Business Survival Foundation</FONT></I>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
</FONT>
<P>
Raymond Keating, Chief Economist at SBSC, criticizes the federal government Superfund program by 
documenting the massive costs and inefficiencies of the Superfund program, which was designed to help 
clean up hazardous waste sites across the country. Keating illustrates how only 18 percent of the worst 
waste sites have been cleaned up at a combined government/private sector cost of roughly $90 million. 
According to Keating, Superfund turned essentially local or state problems into national problems and 
granted the inefficient federal bureaucracy jurisdiction over them. Keating offers a three-step reform 
process for Superfund:<br><ol><li> repeal the retroactive liability for all actions taken before 1987, use science-
based risk assessment and cost-benefit analysis to determine required clean up remedies, and cap the 
number of Superfund sites to gain some control over costs; <li> to bring fairness and common sense, repeal 
the strict, retroactive, and joint and several liability schemes altogether, and only assign liability to 
individuals and businesses who broke the law, and <li> eventually abolish Superfund entirelywaste sites 
are a local problem, not federal.</ol>  28 pp. CONTACT: Small Business Survival Foundation, 1320 18th 
Street, N.W., Suite 200, Washington, DC 20036, 202/785-0238, fax 202/822-8118, e-mail 
<a href="mailto: rstikes@sbsc.org">rstikes@sbsc.org</a>, Internet http://www.sbsc.org.<p>

<B><font size=3>EPA, Industry Still at Odds Over TRI and Materials Accounting 
</FONT></B>
<p>
<I><font size=3>EPA Watch Vol. 5</FONT></I><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman"> No.2 
The DeWeese Company</FONT>
<P>
This issue of EPA Watch features an article on the conflict between EPA and industry over EPAs efforts to 
expand the breadth and depth of the toxic release inventory (TRI) and the controversial issue of material 
accounting. The TRI is the list of chemicals whose emissions certain industries must report annually to 
EPA. EPA is proposing to nearly double the size of this list. Material accounting would require industries 
to report not only emissions, but also the amounts of a certain chemical used at key intervals in the 
manufacturing process. The U.S. Chamber of Commerce led a group of forty companies and trade 
associations in blasting the proposal in a letter to EPA Administrator Carol Browner. They claimed the goal 
of TRI is to provide information to the public so that they can make informed decisions about risk. 
Chemical use is not relative information because it is not a good indicator of risk. On top of that, EPA does 
not have the legislative authority to collect and make public chemical use information. This issue is even 
controversial in the agency itself, as many EPA scientists argue that better use can be made of resources by 
concentrating on more serious risks. 8 pp.  CONTACT: EPA Watch, 14140-L Parke Long Court, Chantilly, 
VA  22021, 703/968-9768.<p>

<a name="crime"</a>
<a href="#table">Table of Contents</a><p>
<center><font size=5>CRIME & LAW</font></center>
<p>
<B><font size=3>Prison Privatization in Pennsylvania 
</FONT></B>
<p>
<I><font size=3>The Commonwealth Foundation</FONT></I>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
</FONT>
<P>
Increasing incarceration rates since 1980 have led to a projected 294 percent increase in the prison 
population of the state of Pennsylvania. The funding for the states corrections department has grown at a 
similar rate. In order to afford new prison construction costs, The Commonwealth Foundation calls for 
privatizing the states prisons. According to this report, privatization saves money because government is 
simply not capable of delivering, running, and regulating services either as efficiently or as effectively as 
private firms. Various studies show that prison privatization would likely save at least 10 percent per year 
in operations costs. This report illustrates how private prisons save operational funds and construction 
costs. It is also shown that private prisons are constitutionally sound. The report concludes that 
privatization of the construction and operation of the new prisons needed in Pennsylvania as of the year 
2000, as well at the operations of existing prisons, is exceptionally attractive financially, and maybe even a 
necessity in times of financial belt-tightening. 20 pp. CONTACT: The Commonwealth Foundation, 600 N. 
Second St., Suite 400, Harrisburg, PA  17101, 717/231-4850, fax 717/617-1905.<p>

<B><font size=3>Juris-Imprudence: Law and Disorder at the Texas Court of Criminal Appeals, 
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">by
Don Willet</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>Texas Public Policy Foundation</FONT></I>
<font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">
</FONT>
<P>
Don Willet, Senior Fellow at the Texas Public Policy Foundation, uncovers the misdeeds of the Texas 
Court of Criminal Appeals (CCA), the highest criminal court in the state of Texas. CCA has an incredible 
record of reversing criminal convictions on appeal due to questionable technicalities. Willet provides 
examples of instances of an excessive pro-defendant tilt. He also illustrates how this court slinks along 
below the radar almost completely unnoticed, except by the victims of the defendants crime. Willet calls 
for reform in the bifurcated Texas judicial system and concludes: only criminals and inefficiency would 
suffer in the Courts absence. 49 pp. CONTACT: Texas Public Policy Foundation, P.O. Box 40519, San 
Antonio, Texas 78229, 210/614-0080, fax 210/614-2649.<p>


<B><font size=3>Conservative and Libertarian Legal Scholarship: An Annotated Bibliography,  
</FONT></B><font size=3 FACE="Times New Roman">prepared by
Roger Clegg and Micheal DeBow</FONT>
<p>
<I><font size=3>The Federalist Society</FONT></I>
