<P>
<B>Strengthening Volunteerism Through Wisconsin's
Welfare-Replacement Proposal: A Brief Examination of Time Dollars,
<BR>
</B>by Michael Hartmann
<P>
<I>Report</I>
Vol. 8, No. 10, Wisconsin Policy Research Institute
<P>
Michael Hartmann, Research Fellow at the Wisconsin
Policy Research Institute, examines the current welfare work-requirement
framework, including Wisconsin's new &quot;W-2&quot; welfare-replacement
program. He uses the ideas of  Edgar Cahn and Marvin Olasky, to
introduce the concept of volunteerism. Both Cahn and Olasky believe
that volunteerism is one of the keys to rebuilding the welfare
system and inner city decay. Hartmann concludes that Cahn's concept
of Time Dollars is something that should be used to help bring
people off of welfare rolls and into the workforce and that solutions
to social problems no longer revolve around traditional liberal
or conservative stances, but around new ideas. 35 pp.  CONTACT:
Wisconsin Policy Research Institute, 3107 N. Shepard Ave., Milwaukee,
WI  53211, 414/963-0600, fax 414/963-4230.<BR>
<P>
<B>Our Hopes Our Dreams: A Vision for America,</B>
<BR>
by Gary Bauer
<P>
Family Research Council
<P>
Gary Bauer, President of the Family Research Council,
addresses several social issues, including education, crime, abortion,
tax cuts, health care, welfare, parents' rights, and the environment
and offers his vision of how to renew America. Bauer concludes
each of the chapters with specific policy recommendations. 164
pp. CONTACT: Family Research Council, 700 Thirteenth street, N.W.,
Suite 500, washington, D.C. 20005, 202/393-2100, fax 202/393-2134.
<BR>
<P>
<B>Is There Life After Big Government? <BR>
The Potential of Civil Society, </B>by
Greg Vanourek, Scott Hamilton &amp; Chester Finn
<P>
Hudson Institute
<P>
This study describes sixteen examples of non-governmental
solutions to social problems and human needs in today's America.
It illustrates effective civic-sector alternatives to government
in such varied domains as crime reduction, education, addiction
treatment, homelessness, community development, and the care of
needy children and the elderly. The authors describe solutions
to social problems produced by ordinary people and contend that
successful programs must be: flexible, demanding, enterprising,
community-based, results-driven, realistic &amp; personal, and
spiritual. 106 pp.  CONTACT: Hudson Institute, Herman Kahn Center,
P.O. Box 26-919, Indianapolis, IN  46226, 317/545-1000, 317/545-9639,
Internet <a href="http://www.hudson.org/hudson">http://www.hudson.org/hudson</a>.<BR>
<P>
<B>Breaking Up Is Easy to Do: A Look at No-Fault
Divorce in the State of Michigan</B>
<P>
Michigan Family Forum
<P>
This paper examines the issue of no-fault divorce
laws in the state of Michigan. The study illustrates that although
children suffer in a divorce, the parents are no-less affected
by the breakup. According to the paper, studies have revealed
that divorced women and men suffer, to a significantly greater
degree than married persons, early death from cancer, cardiovascular
disease, strokes, pneumonia, hypertension, and suicide. The report
concludes that the divorce problem has its roots in both culture
and law, so finding solutions to the current divorce epidemic
needs to encompass both areas. 16 pp.  CONTACT: Michigan Family
Forum, 611 South Walnut. Lansing, MI 48933, 517/374-1171, fax
517/374-6112.
