<h2>Of Note</h2>
<B>Friedrich A. Hayek Fellowships</B>
<P>
The Board of Directors of
The Mont Pelerin Society have announced the Friedrich A. Hayek
Fellowships for the 1996 General Meeting of The Mont Pelerin Society
to be held in Vienna, Austria from September 8th through 13th,
1996. The Hayek Fellowships will be awarded for the three best
essays on the topic: &quot;Responsibility and Choice in a Free
Society.&quot; Essays of not more than 5,000 words may be submitted
by students or young faculty members 35 years of age or younger,
who are not members of The Mont Pelerin Society. The essays will
be judged by a panel of three senior members of The Mont Pelerin
Society. Deadline for submission of essays is April 30, 1996.
First prize Hayek Fellow Award of $2,500 + $1,000 travel grant
to participate in the Society's Vienna meeting. Second prize Hayek
Fellow Award of $1,500 + $1,000 travel grant to participate in
the Society's Vienna meeting. Third prize Hayek Fellow Award of
$1,000 + $1,000 travel grant to participate in the Society's Vienna
meeting. Further information is available from: The Mont Pelerin
Society, P.O. Box 7031, Alexandria, Virginia 22307.<BR>

<P>
<B>Federalist Society Launches Practice Groups</B>
<P>
The Society's fifteen Practice Groups offer members
the opportunity to participate directly in the examination of
problems and issues affecting particular areas of legal practice.
The society seeks through its Practice Groups to counterbalance
bad legal trends that are developing because of government largess,
judicial over-reaching, and the politicization of the organized
bar. There are Practice Groups dealing with the following subjects:
Administrative Law and Regulation; Corporations, Securities, and
Antitrust; Civil Rights; Constitutional Structure; Federalism
and Separation of Powers; Criminal Law and Procedure; Environmental
Law and Property Rights; Financial Institutions; Free Speech and
Election Law; Intellectual Property; International and National
Security Law; Labor and Employment; Litigation; Professional Responsibility,
Legal Ethics, and Legal Education; Religious Liberties; and Telecommunications
and Electronic Media. CONTACT: The Federalist Society, 1700 K
Street, N.W., Suite 901, Washington, D.C. 20006, 202/822-8138,
fax 202/296-8061.<BR>

