<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/wdn.gif" ALT="Washington Bulletin">
<br>
<br>
<P>

<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I>for November 26, 1996</I></CENTER>
<P>
<b>Investment Advice</b><br>
Jim Glassman's "Your Money" column in the Sunday <I>Washington Post</I> focuses on Jim Grant's bearish views. Grant says the stock market has entered its "absurd phase." Yields on dividend-paying stocks have fallen to 2.2 per cent, "even below their level just before the October 1987 crash." The average Standard & Poor p/e ratio recently hit 20, where it was only 15 last year. (Glassman doesn't note that some analysts think structural changes in the economy are raising the trendline p/e ratio.) And then Glassman adds a cute point: "Another danger is that nearly all market advisers think that stocks will keep rising. That's proven to be a negative sign in the past." Grant "believes a decline in the market is imminent, and, if it occurs, investors will not ride it out. They'll sell their funds. Managers will have to dump shares to meet the redemptions, driving prices down further." Glassman thinks, on the other hand, that investors should hold on to their stocks but not buy any new ones.
<P>
<b>Final Notice</b><br>
If you're in the Washington area come see our forum on the politics of abortion on Tuesday, Nov. 26th, from 2-4 p.m., at the Heritage Foundation. Speakers include Karlyn Bowman, Frank Cannon, Maggie Gallagher, James Pinkerton, and Ann Stone. Our own Kate O'Beirne will moderate. 

