<P>

<P>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<I> for November 8, 1996</I></CENTER>
<P>
<b>Spare the Rod</b><br>
	
Conservative activist and strategist Jeff Bell's Parental Rights Amendment, which some social conservatives think of as a silver bullet, was tested in battle in Colorado on Tuesday. It lost, big. Bell explains that the PRA was unable to win any support from Colorado elites, including conservative elites. The Rocky Mountain News, Vincent Carroll, and Bill Armstrong all came out against it. Nobody with authority was willing to counter the canard that the PRA would license child abuse. (Although there really isn't any doubt on that score: previous legal findings of parental rights have had no problems distinguishing between legitimate parental authority and abuse.) Undecided voters tend to break against ballot initiatives; this conservative instinct was mobilized against a conservative reform. Still, Bell isn't too discouraged. He notes that term limits lost its first test, when Washington voters rejected it after a similarly alarmist and misleading campaign. (Washington was supposedly going to lose the benefits of seniority, and then California's delegation would take all its water rights away.) In any case, the point of the PRA campaign is not to win and generate litigation as much as it is to educate the public about the depredations of modern liberalism. The campaign, in other words, is the point. And the campaign continues

<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<P>
