<html>
<body bgcolor="ffffff">
<head>
<title>NR Extra!</title>
</head>
<body>
<p> 
<center><img src="/nationalreview/images/extra.gif" ALT="NR Extra!"></center>
<br>
<br>
<!-------------------------------------------------------------->
<center><b>December 19, 1996</b></center>
<HR WIDTH=50%>
<P>
<P>
<blockquote>



 <LI>Bill Clinton has charged Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle  with the unenviable assignment of negotiating a settlement with Congressional Republicans on the partial-birth abortion ban. His task: get the GOP to exempt  from the ban women whose "health" might be adversely affected by carrying their children to term.  Call it Mission Impossible. Pro-life Republicans know better than to fumble this issue; the Supreme Court has defined "health" so broadly that it includes emotional well-being and maternal youth. And, as Sen. Rick Santorum (R-Penn.) points out, "this procedure would never be used in an emergency," as it takes three days to perform. But given the Republicans' obvious intransigence, it seems peculiar that the President would be so eager to revisit this losing issueunless he fears that the 105th Congress will succeed in overriding his ban. This is a valid concern: Senate Republicans fell only nine votes short of overruling the President in the last term, and in the meantime they have picked up two more seats. Moderate Democratsthose uncomfortable having their names associated with infanticidewill be less likely to succumb to White House arm-twisting when their President is a lame duck, and some have re-election campaigns of their own to worry about in 1998. The hitch is that the President will try to turn the issue against the GOP, chastising its refusal to sign on as gridlock and indifference to women's concerns. 
If Republicans shield their ears from this Sirens' song, however, the public will recognize Clinton's desperation strategy  for what is. Then Congress might just get that override Clinton so fears. 
</blockquote>


